This paper is primarily focused on the analysis of evolutionary algorithms (EAs), which are commonly used in the field of computational intelligence and optimization. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). The paper also uses mathematical tools such as branching processes, which are commonly used in the analysis of algorithms and data structures, suggesting that it could also belong to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also discusses the impact of parameter choices on the performance of EAs, which is a common topic in machine learning and optimization, suggesting that it could also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning) or cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Finally, the paper also discusses the quantitative analysis of fitness functions, which is a common topic in information theory and coding theory, suggesting that it could also belong to cs.IT (Information Theory).
